SIMPLE: postdate
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Postdate
<hw>Post"date`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Postdated</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Postdating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Pref. <ets>post-</ets> +
<ets>date</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To date after the real time;
<as>as, to <ex>postdate</ex> a contract, that is, to date it later than
the time when it was in fact made</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To affix a date to after the event.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Postdate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Postdate
<hw>Post"date`</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Made or done after the date
assigned.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Of these [predictions] some were <qex>postdate</qex>; cunningly
made after the thing came to pass.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Postdate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Postdate
<hw>Post"date`</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A date put to a bill of exchange
or other paper, later than that when it was actually made.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Postdiluvian</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Postdiluvial</ent>⟦br⟧
